-6.  Session ID Allocation
-
-   The Session ID is locally significant to the link.  Allocation
-   strategies depend on the deployment topology:
-
-6.1.  P2P Deployments
-
-   Session IDs MAY be negotiated between peers during Session
-   establishment, or assigned by the Domain Manager during provisioning.
-   Session ID 0 is a valid Session ID (no reserved values).
-
-6.2.  Star Topologies
-
-   The Network Gateway assigns Session IDs and communicates them to
-   Devices during provisioning.  The Gateway maintains the Session ID to
-   handler mapping.
-
-6.3.  Mesh and Other Topologies
-
-   Session IDs MAY be assigned by a Network or Domain Manager, or
-   negotiated between peers.
-
-6.4.  Relay Remapping
-
-   A relay or gateway translating between links MAY remap Session IDs.
-   The Session ID space is local to each link segment; there is no
-   requirement for global uniqueness.
+6.  Session ID Allocation
+
+   The wire Session ID serves as a link-local Discriminator representing
+   the logical Session. Allocation strategies depend on the deployment
+   topology:
+
+6.1.  P2P Deployments
+
+   Session IDs MAY be negotiated between peers during Session
+   establishment, or assigned by the Domain Manager during provisioning.
+   Session ID 0 is a valid Session ID (no reserved values).
+
+6.2.  Star Topologies
+
+   The Network Gateway (acting as a Domain Manager or Instance Manager)
+   assigns Session IDs and communicates them to Devices during provisioning.
+   The Gateway maintains the mapping between link-local Discriminators
+   (Session IDs) and Instances.
+
+6.3.  Mesh and Other Topologies
+
+   Session IDs MAY be assigned by a Network or Domain Manager, or
+   negotiated between peers.
+
+6.4.  Relay Remapping
+
+   A relay or gateway translating between links MAY remap Session IDs
+   (translating the link-local Discriminator). The Session ID space is
+   local to each link segment; there is no requirement for global uniqueness
+   within the Domain for the wire-carried ID.
 
